04436nam a22006255i 9780520975842DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020010961  a97805209758427 a10.1525/97805209758422doi  a(DE-B1597)551593  a(OCoLC)1145925350  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aPN4888.F35bH54 2020 4aPN4888.F35bH54 2020 7aLAN0040002bisacsh04a070.4/32231 aHigdon, Nolan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Anatomy of Fake News :bA Critical News Literacy Education /cNolan Higdon. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Fourth Estate: Democracy and the Press -- t2. The Faux Estate: A Brief History of Fake News in America -- t3. Satirical News and Political Party Propaganda Apparatuses -- t4. The Roots of State-Sponsored Propaganda -- t5. Fake News and the Internet Economy -- t6. Fighting Fake News: Solutions and Discontent -- t7. The Fake News Detection Kit: The Ten-Point Process to Save Our Democracy -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the 2016 US presidential election, debates about fake news have appeared regularly in entertainment, politics, and news media. While many agree on the dangers associated with fake news, there is no consensus around the definition of the phenomenon, and its origins are loosely attributed to a variety of practices and technologies. Much of the discourse has focused on proposing solutions, with media literacy being one of the most frequently mentioned. Nolan Higdon cautions, however, that critical media literacy pedagogy will be unsuccessful without a comprehensive understanding of fake news. The Anatomy of Fake News offers the first examination of fake news for the purpose of creating effective critical news literacy. Higdon employs a critical-historical media ecosystems framework to identify the producers, themes, purposes, and influences of fake news and incorporates his findings into an invaluable fake news detection kit. This much-needed resource provides a rich history of fake news and a promising set of pedagogical strategies for mitigating its pernicious influence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aFake newszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMedia literacyxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069041540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520975842zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520975842423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520975842.jpg  a978-3-11-069041-5  UC Press Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070472-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-SEWb2020